DUBLIN -- Ireland 's European and local elections on Friday pose a serious midterm test for the two - party coalition led by Irish Prime Minister Enda Kenny -- its first since it swept to power at the height of the country 's crisis more than three years ago .
Ireland has been hailed by the European Union as the poster child for austerity and its exit from its three - year bailout in December cited as proof for what compliant countries can achieve .

However , two weekend opinion polls suggest disenchanted voters are far less impressed by Europe 's austerity prescription and will give the Irish government a severe bloody nose in the European and local elections .

Despite signs that Ireland has weathered the worst of its huge banking debt crisis that brought the country close to bankruptcy six years ago , support for the coalition has fallen , the polls suggest .

There is strong evidence that employment is growing rapidly again , but with unemployment and emigration still at elevated levels , austerity taxes and large household debts , a legacy of the banking bust , continue to weigh on voters .
